MANLEY-REGAN TEST TEAM ARRIVED AND OFF LOADED 295 GALLONS FROM LEAKING CONTAINER TO 6 UN CONTAINERS. SPILLAGE INSIDE TRAILER WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH PER MSDS AND CLEANED UP. PRODUCT AND CLEAN-UP WAS RETURNED TO MANLEY-REGAN FACILITY FOR RE-USE. IBC WAS CRACKED ON BOTTOM. CONTAINER WAS HANDLED BY ANOTHER CUSTOMER PRIOR TO DISCOVERY OF LEAK. CONTAINER WAS TESTED ON 8-97 AND FILLED ON 1-29-99. IT HAS CRACK ON BOTTOM NEAR FORK POCKETS. POSSIBLE CAUSE - MISHANDLING BY FORKLIFT BUT CANNOT BE CONFIRMED. IBC WILL BE DESTROYED. REF 016-2299 REPORT ATTACHED.

DRIVER WAS ENROUTE AND TRAILER DEVELOPED A MECHANICAL PROBLEM ( LEAKING AIR TANK) AND WAS SENT TO THE REPAIR SHOP. WHILE AT THE REPAIR SHOP THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A VERY SLOW DRIP ( 1 DRIP EVERY 10 MINUTES) FROM A WELDED SEAM ON THE CARGO TANK. HE SUMMONED ADVICE FROM HIS DISPATCHER WHO SENT ANOTHER PERSON TO VERIFY THE DRIP WAS ACTUALLY PRODUCT. THE DISPATCHER COMMITTED AN ERROR IN ORDERING THE DRIVER TO REMOVE THE CARGO TANK FROM THE ORIGINAL LOCATION WHERE THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED, AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO TAKE CARGO TANK  BACK TO THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION FOR THE PRODUCT TO BE OFF-LOADED. REMEDIAL TRAINING IS SCHEDULED FOR THE DRIVER AND THE DISPATCHER.

IN THE PROCESS OF PUMPING OFF PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK WITH PUMP LOCATED ON THE TRACTOR, THE REAR SEAL STARTED TO FAIL. THE CAUSED  A DRIP FROM THE PUMP. ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT SOCKS AND CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE AND DISPOSED OF.

DRIVER PUT PUMP IN GEAR AND STARTED PRODUCT FLOW. CONSIGNEE WAS PUTTING PRODUCT INTO TOTES. THE DRUMMING NOZZLE SPIT APART SPRAYING BOTH OF THE CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEES. APPROXIMATELY 10 TO 15 GALLONS RAN OUT ONTO LOADING AREA. CONSIGNEE PUT OIL DRY ON IT THEN SWEPT IT UP. TWO EMPLOYEES WERE SENT TO THEIR FAMILY DOCTORS TO BE CHECKED OUT. THEY WERE OKAY AND RETURNED TO WORK.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: THIS SHIPMENT SPILLED WHILE IN THE WAREHOUSE ON THE FLOOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THERE WERE FIVE FIRE EXTINGUISHER INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  THE MARKINGS ON THE FIRE EXTINGUISHES THEMSELVES WERE: DOT SPEC MH 948803, NP338204, NP748177, MH 947855.  THE OUTER BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKING OR LABELING AND IT WAS NOT SENT WITH A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  IT IS THEREFORE BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY "FIRE EXTINGUISHES," UN1044.  THE FAA AGENT DENNIS HARWELL WAS NOTIFIED. FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING F.A.A. INVESTIGATION.

DURING THE INBOUND SORT OPERATION, ONE OF THE STATION MANAGERS NOTICED THAT THIS PACKAGE WAS STAINED AND WAS GIVING OFF A FUEL ODOR.  THE FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST WAS ALERTED AND UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER PACKAGE DURING THE CLEANUP PROCEDURE, HE FOUND THAT THIS WAS A FUEL CONTROL UNIT THAT WAS WRAPPED IN SOAKED PLASTIC WRAP OR LINING.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS AND LABELING ON THE OUTER PACKAGE, SO THE FAA WAS ALERTED ABOUT THIS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  THERE WAS ALSO NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK PROVIDED TO FEDEX.  THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD FOR THE FAA PENDING THE OUTCOME OF THEIR INVESTIGATION.

THE WAREHOUSEMAN ABSORBED THE SPILLED WASTE AND PLACED THE LEAKING 30 GALLON DRUM INTO A 55 GALLON OVERPACK. THIS INCIDENT GENERATED APPROXIMATELY THREE POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DR. SE, HEBRON FOR RECYCLING. AFTER UNLOADING AT LANGLEY AFB, VA ON 2/20/99 WHERE STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE IS FOR DOME LIDS TO BE OPEN DURING UNLOADING, THE DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE AND SECURE THE DOME LID. WHEN HIS VEHICLE APPROACHED THE RED TRAFFIC SIGNAL HE APPLIED HIS BRAKES SO THAT HE COULD STOP AND MAKE A LEFT TURN. WHEN HE APPLIED HIS BRAKES PRODUCT INSIDE THE TANK SURGED FORWARD AND ABOUT 20 GALLONS SPILLED OUT THE OPEN DOME LID. THE PRODUCT FLOWED THROUGH THE TWO INCH DRAIN HOSE ONTO THE ROADWAY IN THE LEFT TURN LANE WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED UNTIL IT WAS CLEANED UP AND REMOVED BY THE VIRGINA BEACH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CLEAN UP DIVISION. A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ALSO NEEDED TO BE CLEANED UP NEAR THE ACCESS GATE TO THE NORFOLK AIRPORT DELIVERY POINT FROM HARD SURFACE ROAD.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS PROCEEDING NB ON HWY. 21. IT STARTED TO PASS A PICK UP TRUCK THAT WAS MOVING SLOWLY IN THE RIGHT LANE. AS OUR VEHICLE STARTED TO PASS THE PICK UP TRUCK, THE THE PICK UP TRUCK TURNED ABRUPTLY INTO OUR TRACTOR, WITHOUT ANY PRIOR WARNING. THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK LATER SAID SHE WAS ATTEMTING TO MAKE A U-TURN. AFTER THE COLLISION, OUR TRACTOR AND TANK TRAILER OVERTURNED ONTO  ITS SIDE, BLOCKING BOTH NB LANES OF HWY 21. PHOSPHORIC ACID DRIPPED FROM THE DOME LID AND THE WASH-OUT PORTS, UNTIL THESE OPENINGS WERE TIGHTENED DOWN . SOME DIESEL FUEL LEAKED, AS WELL. ALL OF THE LEAKS WERE CONTAINED AND REMEDIATED. NO INJURIES RESULTED FROM THE LEAK OF PHOSPHORIC ACID. THE INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED AS RESULT OF THE COLLISION. THE WASTE HAS BEEN PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2045 HOURS, FEBRUARY 2, 1999, AT OAK ISLAND YARK IN NEWARK, NEW JERSEY, CONRAIL TRAIN PLOL1B SHOVING WEST OFF HUMP LEAD #10. LEAD CAR CR884549 DERAILED AT #11 SWITCH (RUN THROUGH SWITCH). TOTAL OF FOUR RAILCARS DERAILED IN PIOI1B AND TWO TANK CARS EFFECTED ON TRACK #12. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. TILX200113, CONTAINING NITRIC ACID DERAILED AND ROLLED 90 DEGREES TO ITS LEFT SIDE. INSPECTION AT TIME OF INCIDENT, AND AFTER RERAILING AT 1100 HOURS, FEBRUARY 3, 1999, BY CONRAIL'S MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER, CUSTOMER REPRESENTATIVES AND REACT, NOTED SCRAPING OF PAINT/SHELL ON LEFT SIDE OF CAR. HOWEVER, DUE TO SEVERE STRUCTURAL DAMAGE TO BOTH ENDS OF THE CAR (BENT SILLS), THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR. NEGLIGIBLE RESIDUE OF PRODUCT NOTED INSIDE HOUSING AREA, SUSPECTED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE PARTIALLY OPENING AS THE CAR ROLLED. TILX200125 CONTAINING NITRIC ACID ROLLED 45 DEGREES TO ITS RIGHT SIDE. NEGLIGIBLE PRODUCT RESIDUE INSIDE HOUSING, SUSPECTED FROM PARTIAL OPENING OF SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AS CAR ROLLED. AT 0900 HOURS, FEBRUARY 3, 1999, THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED. INSPECTION OF TANK SHELL (NON-INSULATED) AND MECHANICAL APPURTENANCES CONDUCTED BY CONRAIL'S MECHANICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER, CUSTOMER REPRESENTATIVES AND REACT. DUE TO SEVERELY BENT AND CRACKED BODY BOLSTER, THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR. ECUX 408227, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, NOR DID NOT RELEASE ANY PRODUCT. ONLY VERY MINOR JACKET IMPACT AND ONE SET/END TRUCKS DERAILED. THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED, SENT TO SHOP FOR ROLLER BEARING INSPECTION, AND FORWARDED TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION. THE DERAILMENT WAS CAUSED BY A RUN THROUGH SWITCH.

NEGLIGIBLE RESIDUE OF PRODUCT NOTED INSIDE HOUSING AREA, SUSPECTED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE PARTIALLY OPENING AS THE CAR ROLLED. TILX200125 CONTAINING NITRIC ACID ROLLED 45 DEGREES TO ITS RIGHT SIDE. NEGLIGIBLE PRODUCT RESIDUE INSIDE HOUSING, SUSPECTED FROM PARTIAL OPENING OF SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AS CAR ROLLED. AT 0900 HOURS, FEBRUARY 3, 1999, THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED. INSPECTION OF TANK SHELL (NON-INSULATED) AND MECHANICAL APPURTENANCES CONDUCTED BY CONRAIL'S MECHANICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER, CUSTOMER REPRESENTATIVES AND REACT. DUE TO SEVERELY BENT AND CRACKED BODY BOLSTER, THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR. ECUX 408227, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, NOR DID NOT RELEASE ANY PRODUCT. ONLY VERY MINOR JACKET IMPACT AND ONE SET/END TRUCKS DERAILED. THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED, SENT TO SHOP FOR ROLLER BEARING INSPECTION, AND FORWARDED TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION. THE DERAILMENT WAS CAUSED BY A RUN THROUGH SWITCH.

DIESEL WAS UNLOADED INTO ABOVE GROUND TANK AND THE SUBJECT TANK DID NOT HAVE SUFFICIENT AVAIILABLE CAPACITY. APPROX.. 25 GALLONS OVERFLOWED INTO THE  CONCRETE DIKE. THE HAS A RECOVERY SYSTEM AND THE DIESEL WAS RETURNED TO THR TANK. CORRECTIVE  ACTION : 1) INSTRUCTED DRIVER TO COMMUNICATE WITH CUSTOMER FOR UNLOADING INSTRUCTIONS. 2) ASK CUSTOMER TO INSTALL GAUGING FOR TANK.

TWO OF SIX MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, GATX 54670, FEBRUARY 6, 1999, PITTSBURGH DIVISON AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOIURS, SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 6, 1999 AT CONRAIL'S CONWAY YARD, IN CONWAY, PA, A CONRAIL YARD CREW REPORTED A POSSIBLE PRODUCT LEAK FROM TANK CAR GATX 54670 CONTAINING STYRENE MONOMER, INHIBITED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1907 HOURS, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND UPON FUTHER EXAMINATION, DETERMINED THE TANK CAR HAD TWO (2) OF SIX (6) MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE. column168: Storage tanks at the site were mis-marked. Veter route labels were not consistent with tank markings. Spill occurred. Officials at the site determined that the cause for this was driver error.

Driver loaded the trailer with Jet A. When he finished, before leaving the rack, he noticed a small drip by the fire valve of #5 compartment. He brought the load back to the yard. The mechanic and the driver were transferring the load to another trailer and tried to put 1200 gallons into a 1000 gallon compartment causing the spill. When I was notified, I went and got ten bags of floor dry. We also rented a small bobcat to put the contaminated dirt on a heavy tapr. We covered the dirt with another heavy tarp. To prevent further incidents like this from happening, drivers have been instructed to double check compartment sizes, including checking the spec plate if needed. If they are still unsure, don't do anything until they are sure of the compartment size.

Spillage left from the loading process, NATX 25397 and NATX 25356, February 10, 1999, Indianapolis Division. At approximately 1115 hours, Wednesday, February 10, 1999, at Conrail's Buckeye yard in Columbus, Ohio, a Conrail car shop repairman discovered a negligible amount of product on the top and slightly down the side of tank cars NATX 25397 and NATX 25356 both containing Petroleum crude oil. Appropriate notification made. A representative from the shipper, Ohio Oil Gathering arrived at the site, examined the tank car and determined that there was spillage left from the loading process. Ohio Oil Gathering checked the gaskets and fittings and all were found secured. The spilled area was also cleaned. The tank car was okayed for transportation and sent to destination.

column168: INSPECTION OF INBOUND CSXT I/C BY CAR FOREMAN D COLLINS FOUND TANK CAR OF METHANOL (SEE CAR NUMBER ABOVE) TO BE VENTILATING, FORCING PRODUCT TO RUN DOWN SIDES OF CAR AND DRIP ON GROUND.  REMEDIAL ACTION TAKEN:  CAR DEPARTMENT PLACED TARPS AND ABSORBENT PILLOWS UNDER CAR TO CONTAIN LEAKAGE.  BANGOR TWP., FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED TO THE SCENE AND SPRAYED THE CAR WITH WATER AND FOAM TO COOL IT DOWN.  YOUNGS ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP WAS CALLED AND UPON ARRIVAL AND FOUND CAR TO BE LEAKING AT A RATE OF 0.5 - 1 GALLON PER MINUTE FROM THE TOP UNLOADING VALVE ASSEMBLY.  APPROXIMATELY 20-40 GALLONS OF METHANOL ESCAPED FROM THE 3 INCH SIPHON VALVE ON TOP OF THE CAR, FROM POSSIBLE OVERLOADING AND/OF EXPANSION DUE TO TEMPERATURE CHANGE.  YOUNGS APPROACHED THE CAR AND RELIEVED INTERNAL PRESSURE BY OPERATING THE ONE INCH AIR VALVE.  INTERNAL VAPORS WERE ALLOWED TO VENT INTO THE ATMOSPHERE UNTIL EQUALISATION WAS REACHED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THREADED END PLUGS, ATTACHED TO THE AIR VALVE AND SIPHON VALVE WERE CLEANED, TAPED WITH TEFLON RE APPLIED AND TIGHTENED.  THE TANK CAR HOUSING AND FITTINGS WERE WIPED DOWN AND PROTECTIVE COVER SECURED.  YOUNGS THEN COLLECTED FREE PHASE PRODUCT REMAINING ON THE GROUND SURFACE AND FIELD SCREENED THEM FOR COMBUSTIBILITY UTILIZING THE "HAZCAT CHEMICAL INDICATION SYSTEM" DEVELOPED BY HAZTECH SYSTEMS INC.  ALL LIQUIDS COLLECTED WERE DETERMINED TO BE NON-FLAMMABLE IN NATURE.  ***PLEASE SEE ATTACHED FOR MORE INFORMATION***  AT THE REQUEST OF METHANEX CORP., LAKE STATE RAILWAY COMPANY AND THE MDEQ, YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL RETURNED TO THE SPILL SITE ON 02/12/1999 AND COLLECTED SIX(6) SOIL SAMPLES FROM 3 FEET BELOW SURFACE GRADE (BSG) IMMEDIATELY SURROUNDING THE PREVIOUS LOCATION OF THE FORMER LEAKING RAIL CAR.  (1) BALLAST AND SOIL SAMPLE WAS COLLECTED FROM BETWEEN THE RAILS DIRECTLY BENEATH THE CAR AND FIVE (5) SOIL SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED IMMEDIATELY EAST AND WEST OF THE FORMER TANK CAR LOCATION. SAMPLES WERE SUBSEQUENTLY SUBMITTED TO BRIGHTON ANALYTICAL, INC., OF BRIGHTON, MI., FOR ANALYSIS OF METHANOL UTILIZING UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (USEPA) APPROVED TEST METHOD 8015. CONCENTRATIONS OF METHANOL WERE NOT DETECTED AT OR ABOVE MDEQ RESIDENTIAL AND COMMERCIAL I GENERIC CLEAN-UP CRITERIA AND SCREENING LEVELS ESTABLISHED FOR SOIL IN THE REVISED PART 201 OPERATIONAL MEMORANDUM #18 CLEAN-UP CRITERIA TABLES.  SOIL SAMPLE #6 TAKEN FROM THE EAST SIDE - NORTH END, EXHIBITED THE HIGHEST CONCENTRATION OF METHANOL (45,000 PARTS PER BILLION (PPB) ), SUBSTANTIALLY LOWER THAN RESIDENTIAL/COMMERCIAL I DRINKING WATER PROTECTION CRITERIA OF 74,000 PPB.  DURING CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES, YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL CHECKED ALL NEARBY CATCH BASINS, SURPS, DRAINS, PITS AND OTHER POTENTIAL MIGRATORY PATHWAYS FOR INDICATION OF METHANOL CONTAMINATION.  THE LARGE AMOUNT OF RAIN AND METHANOL'S WATER SOLUBILITY MASKED ANY EVIDENCE OF IMPACT IN THESE AREAS.  NO OTHER MIGRATORY PATHWAYS WERE DETECTED.  BASED ON THE ABOVE ACTIVITIES AND OBSERVATIO

OF THE FIVE CARS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT DERAILED, THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 0215 HOURS, FEBRUARY 10, 1999, AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE UNTIL THE TANK CARS WERE UP RIGHTED, THERE WAS A VOLUNTARY EVACUATION OF 80 HOMES. THE DERAILMENT WAS CAUSED BY A SUSPECTED WIDE GAUGE.

LOOSE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE, GATX 294340 FEBRUARY 15, 1999, INDIANAPOLIS DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS, MONDAY FEBRUARY 15, 1999, WHILE WORKING 12 PRODUCT LEAKING DOWN THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANK CAR GATX 29434 CONTAINING METHANOL.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  CONRAIL'S CAR FOREMAN ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WHERE IT THREADS ONTO THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE FLANGE WAS LEAKING.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAILS'S CAR FOREMAN WHO MADE ONE AND ONE HALF TURNS ON THE VALVE TO SECURE IT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1450 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, OKAY FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

DRIVER'S STATEMENT:  ON OR ABOUT 1300 P.M.,WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY AT INTERNATIONAL PAPER THERE WAS A FIVE GALLONS BUCKET IN BETWEEN THAT PALLET AN A PALLET FOR YANCY BROTHERS PRO #89915376-4.  THE BUCKET WAS CRACKED ON THE SIDE AND HAD LEAKED MOST OF THE CONTENTS OUT OF IT.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE DISPATCHER.  NO DUNNAGE USED.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THERE WAS A DRIP LEAKAGE FROM THE HOSE THAT WA CLOSEST TO THE TRAILER OUTLET.  THIS CAUSED PRODUCT TO DRIP INTO A PUDDLE OF WATER IN A DEPRESSION OF THE PAVED SURFACE OF CONSIGNEE'S YARD.  WHEN DELIVERY WAS FINISHED, CONSIGNEE AND DRIVER NOTICED THIS WATER WITH PRODUCT FLOATING ON THE SURFACE AND CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL CLEANED UP BY PUMPING THE WATER AND PRODUCT INTO A DRUM.  ESTIMATED 30 GALLONS OF WATER AND ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT. THERE WAS NO INJURIES AND NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAY.  CARRIER ARRANGED FOR DISPOSAL FIRM TO PICK UP THE DRUM OF CONTAMINATED WATER AND SEND IT FOR DISPOSAL ACCORDING TO APPLICABLE LAWS.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A DRIVER DROPPED A 5 GALLON DRUM WHILE UNLOADING THE DRUM FROM HIS VEHICLE. THE BUNG CAME LOOSE ON THE DRUM WHEN IT STRUCK THE GROUND ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF WASTE TO SPILL ON THE CONCRETE SURFACE. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS ALSO OVER PACKED INTO A SEPARATE CONTAINER. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH ST., DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS BREIFED TO USE MORE CARE WHILE LOADING THE DRUMS ONTO HIS VEHICLE.

A DRIVER DISCOVERED A LEAKING DRUM IN HIS TRUCK WHEN HE WENT TO UNLOAD HIS VEHICLE. APPROX. 3 GALLONS OF WASTE HAD LEAKED INTO THE REAR OF HIS TRUCK FROM THE DRUM GASKET. THE DRIVER ABSORBED AND RECOVERED THE SPILLED MATERIAL INTO AN OVER PACK AND TIGHTENED THE LID ON THE LEAKING CONTAINER. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROX. 30 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY - KLEEN FACILITY AT 960 TURNPIKE ST, CANTON MA FOR STORAGE PENDING TRANSFER FOR FINAL TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS BRIEFED TO INSPECT DRUMS FOR LOOSE LIDS PRIOR TO LOADING THEM ONTO HIS VEHICLE.

WHILE UNLOADING A PALLET FROM HIS VEHICLE A DRIVER DROPPED ONE 16 GALLON DRUM ONTO THE GROUND. WHEN THE DRUM STRUCK THE PAVEMENT IT LEAKED APPROX. 8 OUNCES OF WASTE. THE DRIVER ABSORBED AND RECOVERED THE SPILLED MATERIAL INTO AN OVER PACK AND TIGHTENED THE LID ON THE DROPPED DRUM. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROX. 1 POUND OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE , TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DR SE, HEBRON, OH FOR TREATMENT DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS BRIEFED TO USE MORE CARE WHILE UNLOADING DRUMS FROM HIS VEHICLE.

WHILE A WAREHOUSE MAN WAS PLACING 30 GALLON DRUMS ON A WOODEN PALLET IT BROKE AND ONE OF THE DRUMS TIPPED OVER LEAKING ONE GALLON OF WASTE THROUGH THE GASKET. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK. THE LID WAS TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING DRUM. THIS SPILLED GENERATED APPROX. 10 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 6182 OLD MENDENAHALL RD, ARCHDALE, NC FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE ENROUTE TO FINAL TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE WAREHOUSE MAN WAS BRIEFED TO INSPECT PALLETS FOR SERVICE ABILITY PRIOR TO LOADING DRUMS ON THEM.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Derailment; Rollover Accident
column168: A DERAILMENT OCCURRED CAUSING THE OVERTURNING OF 3 RAIL CARS (TOLUENE) AND LPG) AND THE OVERTURNING OF THE 4TH. ONE RAIL CAR LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF TOLUENE WHEN A VACUUM VALVE FITTING MALFUNCTIONED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF 100-150 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO THE GROUND. DAVIS COUNTY FIRE DEPT., WOODS CROSS POLICE, DAVIS COUNTY SHERIFF, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD AND TW COMPANY WERE CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE DERAILMENT. BECAUSE OF THE POTENTIAL FOR HEALTH AND FIRE PROBLEMS, RESIDENTS NEAR THE DERAILMENT WERE EVACUATED. CREWS STOPPED THE LEAK AND TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT TO TANK TRUCKS. THE NON-LEAKING RAIL CARS WERE UP RIGHTED. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND IS BEING PROFILED FOR DISPOSAL AT AN EPA APPROVED TSDF. OTHER LPG CARS AND TOLUENE CARS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT BUT DID NOT LEAK.

PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED AT CUSTOMER'S FACILITY IN TRUCK PUMP. THE MATERIAL WAS PUMPED INTO A PREASSIGNED TANK APPROXIMATELY 40% THE OPERATOR INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO STOP PUMPING. THE DRIVER STOPPED THE PUMP UNHOOKED THE HOSE AND WALKED THE LINE OUT. THE OPERATOR THEN PROCEEDED TO CLOSE THE GATE VALVE ON THE TANK BUT, DID NOT FULLY CLOSE THE VALVE CREATING BACK PRESSURE TO FORCE THE PRODUCT THROUGH THE LINE, TRUCK PUMP, AND ONTO THE GROUND. THIS YIELDED APPROX. 2-3 GALS. THE OPERATOR CHECKED THE TANK AGAIN AND ASKED THE DRIVER TO PROCEED PUMPING OFF AT THIS POINT, THE DRIVE PUMPED FOR ABOUT 2-3 MINS. BEFORE THE PRODUCT BEGIN TO COME OUT OF AVENT LINE FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK. THIS YIELDED APPROX. 10 GALLONS. THE TWO SPILLS WERE BOTH IN CONTAINED AREAS AND WERE CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY AND DISPOSED OF BY THE CUSTOMERS. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: THE DRIVER WILL MAINTAIN A CLOSED SYSTEM (NO OPEN HOSES AND VALVES) ON THE PUMP OFF SITE.

column168: CARRIER'S DOCK EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED A PACKAGED ON THE DOCK FLOOR WITH APPARENT LEAKAGE FROM IT.  EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE MATERIAL WHILE INVESTIGATING THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  UPON REPORTING THE INCIDENT TO HIS SUPERVISOR, THE EMPLOYEE WAS DIRECTED TO A DECONTAMINATION SHOWER, THEN TRANSPORTED NON-EMERGENCY TO A MEDICAL FACILITY.  AFTER TREATMENT FOR CHEMICAL EXPOSURE HE WAS RELEASED. THE EMPLOYEE WAS DISMISSED FROM WORK FOR THE BALANCE OF THE SHIFT. HE REPORTED FOR WORK FOR HIS NEXT SCHEDULED SHIFT WITH NO FURTHER ILL EFFECTS, AND HAS EXHIBITED NONE SINCE.  THE PACKAGE OF H/M WAS OVERPACKED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

DURING THE LOADING PROCESS, THE DRIVER HAD TIED THE LOADING NOZZLE IN THE OPEN POSITION, THUS DEFEATING THE AUTOMATIC SHUT OFF FEATURE. THE TRUCK BEGAN TO OVERFLOW WHILE THE DRIVER WAS AT THE OTHER END OF THE TOP OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER HAD TO RUN BACK AND UNTIE NOZZLE TO STOP THE OVERFLOW.  TERMINAL STAFF CLEANED UP SPILLED PRODUCT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.  AT A SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATIVE MEETING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL INDICATED THAT TYING DOWN THE NOZZLE IS ACCEPTABLE.  THE MANAGEMENT OF THE FACILITY NOTED THIS AND INDICATED THAT CORRECTIVE ACTION WILL OCCUR.  THE TYING DOWN OF THE NOZZLE WILL NOT BE AN OPTION ON FUTURE LOADINGS.

column168: DURING THE UNLOAD PROCESS THE MAIN PRODUCT HOSE DEVELOPED A ONE AND ONE-HALF INCH HOLE. DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PROCESS AND CHANGED HOSES. THE PERSONNEL AT THE CUSTOMER PLANT PERFORMED NEUTRALIZATION AND CLEANUP OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

MOTORIST FLAGGED DOWN TRUCK EN ROUTE AND NOTED THAT A MIST OF PRODUCT HAD SPRAYED FROM A CLEAN OUT CAP ON TOP OF TRAILER AS IT CHANGED FROM ONE ROUTE TO ANOTHER.  THE DRIVER STOPPED AND TIGHTENED THE CLEAN OUT CAP.  THE ONLY PRODUCT THAT COULD BE FOUND WAS ON THE AUTOMOBILE OF THE MOTORIST.  THE MOTORIST'S INSURANCE COMPANY CLAIMED SUBROGATED LOSSES AGAINST OUR INSURANCE CARRIER.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

DURING THE UNLOAD PROCESS A VAPOR VALVE ON THE SHIPPER OWNED TANK CARGO TRAILER MALFUNCTIONED - SPRAYING PRODUCT ON SAME TRAILER AND THE ONE NEXT TO IT, AND SOME ON THE SOIL. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL REMEDIATED THE SOIL AND PILED THE AFFECTED SOIL ON PLASTIC. CARRIER'S INSURANCE COMPANY SENT AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY TO HAUL THE SOIL AWAY, AND WIPE DOWN THE TRAILER EXTERIORS WITH SPECIAL PADS. THERE WAS ON INJURY. NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY. THE MALFUNCTIONING VALVE WAS REPAIRED.

TRAILER WA SIN THE REPAIR SHOP FOR OTHER MAINTENANCE ISSUE WHILE LOADED AND IT WAS NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A SLOW DRIP FROM THE TRAILER BOTTOM PANELS. PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A DIFFERENT CARGO TANK. SPILLED MATERIAL  WAS CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY STORED FOR DISPOSAL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

column168: WHILE LOADING A RAIL CAR WITH A SPENT CAUSTIC SODA SOLUTION, THE RAIL CAR VENTED AND RELEASED 50 GALLONS FROM THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM AND VENT WHICH IS ASSOCIATED WITH THE RAIL CAR.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD AND SOIL. THE RAIL CAR WAS SECURED AND THE VENT CANISTERS ISOLATED.  THE CONCRETE AREA AND RAIL CAR WAS WASHED DOWN AND THE GENERATED WASTE PUMPED BACK INTO A HOLDING TANK.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO 55-GALLON DRUMS. THE SHIPPING PAPERS HAD NOT YET BEEN GENERATED AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 500 POUNDS OF WASTE.  THE LIQUID PORTION OF THE WASTE WAS PUT BACK INTO THE FEED TANK AT THE EAST CHICAGO FACILITY FOR RECOVERY. THE SOLID WASTE GENERATED WAS TRANSPORTED TO A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DALTON, IL FOR FUEL BLENDING.  THE EMPLOYEE LOADING THE RAIL CAR WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: EACH 150LB, CHLORINE CYLINDER COMES WITH A BRASS VALVE THAT IS THREADED INTO THE TOP OF IT.  EACH VALVE IS EQUIPED WITH A FUSE PLUG THAT IS EST TO MELT AT 158 DEGREES F, WHICH WILL PREVENT STATIC RUPTURE OF THE CYLINDER. THE FUSE PLUG IN THE POINT WHERE THE RELEASE TOOLS PLACE ON CYLINDER 2739. THE CYLINDER WAS FILLED WITH CHLORINE AT OUR CHATTANOOGA FACILITY ON 2/17/99.  IT WAS LOADED ON THE TRAILER AND DELIVERED TO OUR MIDWAY FACILITY ON THE EARLY MORNING ON 2/18/99.  SEVERAL HOUSE LATER EMPLOYEES OF THE MIDWAY FACILITY COME IN TO WORK AND BACKED THE TRAILER WITH THE CYLINDER ON IT TO THE DOCK TO BE UNLOADED.  WHEN THEY OPENED THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER THEY COULD SMELL CHLORINE.  AFTER LOOKING FOR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK THEY FOUND CYLINDER 2739 THAT WAS LEAKING AT THE FUSE PLUG.  THE CYLINDER WAS PLACED INTO A CYLINDER CONTAINMENT VESSEL FOR TRANSFER BACK TO CHATTANOOGA ALL CYLINDER VALVES ARE TESTED AT 500 PSIG TO ENSURE THAT THE FUSE PLUG WILL NOT LEAK.

column168: ONE COMPARTMENT OF A MULTI COMPARTMENT TANKER WAS PARKED IN A CONTAINMENT BASIN, AND UNLOADED INTO DRUMS, BY PM SHIFT OPERATORS. DRIVER ARRIVED EARLY AM TO PICK UP EMPTY TANKER FOR SUBSEQUENT LOADING AT ANOTHER TERMINAL. THE TANKER HAD BEEN PARKED UPON A SLOPE SUCH THAT THE COMPARTMENT DID NOT DRAIN COMPLETELY. PM OPERATORS FAILED TO CLOSE BOTTOM VALVE UPON UNLOADING, PER SOP. UPON MOVING THE TRAILER FROM THE SLOPED AREA, THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE COMPARTMENT SPILLED FROM THE VALVE UPON AND ASPHALT DRIVE AREA. VEHICLE WAS DRIVEN IN CLOCKWISE SEMI CIRCLE TO SCALE AREA AND DRIVER FAILED TO RECOGNIZE THE RELEASE. XYLENE ABSORBED INTO ASPHALT FREE LIQUID WAS OBSERVED AND DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. LOSS ESTIMATED IN EXCESS OF 100 LBS. REPORT FILED WITH THE NRC. NO FURTHER ACTIONS TAKEN.

ON TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 9,1999, WE RECEIVED AN ORDER TO DELIVER 4,500 GALLONS OF HEATING FUEL #2 TO THE FEDERAL BUILDING AND THEIR 15,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND FUEL TANK. AT APPROX. 12:40 PM, OUR DRIVER NOTICED THE VENT SPITTING OUT SOME FUEL. ONLY 4318 GALLONS HAD BEEN DISCHARGED INTO STORAGE AT THAT POINT. WHEN THE DRIVER CRACKED ONE OF THE DOG EARS ON THE CAMLOCK FITTING, THE BACK PRESSURE THAT HAD BUILT UP SPRAYED AN ESTIMATED 20 GALLONS INTO THE PARKING LOT AREA. IT WAS LATER LEARNED THAT APPROX. ANOTHER 200 GALLONS HAD LEAKED INTO THE BASEMENT OF THE FEDERAL BUILDING. THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED DUE TO FUMES THAT BEGAN TO PERMEATE THE BUILDING AND THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS BEGAN. EVIDENTLY, THE VEEDER-ROOT TANK MONITORING SYSTEM AT THE FEDERAL BUILDING HAD FAILED AND THERE ARE NO GAUGE CHARTS TO COMPARE THE AMOUNT OF FUEL "ORDERED" AGAINST THE ACTUAL TANK GAUGES. AS OF THIS DATA (04-09-01), THE FEDERAL BUILDING HAS NOT PROVIDED A TANK CHART AND IS STILL DEPENDING ON THE SAME VEEDER-ROOT TANK MONITORING APPARATUS.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE REPORTS WE RECEIVED, AND IBC SHIFTED DURING TRANSPORT ON A RURAL, GRAVEL ROAD.  WHEN THE IBC SHIFTED THE VALVE OPENED AND A SMALL AMOUNT, NO MORE THAN 100 GAL., WAS SPILLED FROM THE CONTAINER.  WE HAD NO DAMAGED IBCS WHICH WOULD HAVE INDICATED THE "SHEARING OFF" OF A VALVE.  AS SUCH PLEASE NOTE THAT THE PACKAGE MARKINGS LISTED IN SECTION VII ARE GENERAL MARKINGS AS WOULD APPEAR ON OTHER SIMILAR PACKAGES.  WHEN THE TRUCK MAKING THIS DELIVERY RETURNED TO OUR FACILITY THERE WAS PRODUCT IN THE IBC. THERE HAD BEEN 5 SIMILAR IBCS ON THE DELIVERY AND ALL PRODUCT WAS ACCOUNTED FOR.  IN A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT WE HAVE PUT INTO EFFECT BETTER TRACKING PROCEDURES - THAT WOULD MAKE OUR WAREHOUSE STAFF IMMEDIATELY AWARE OF ANY PRODUCT QUANTITY DISCREPANCY.  IMMEDIATELY UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE SITUATION WE CONTACTED OUR ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTING FIRM, PLEASE SEE ATTACHED REPORT.  WE HAVE ALSO PUT INTO PLACE MORE DETAILED CHECKLISTS FOR OUR WAREHOUSE STAFF, DRIVERS AND MANAGEMENT.

MGR. CTS DENNIS JOHNSON WAS ADVISED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE PHOENIX YARD.  UPON INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE TOP OPERATING HANDLE WAS NOT SECURE. AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS.  MGR.  RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM MR. JOHN LYON M.T.O. AT OGDEN UT., THAT TANK CAR UTLX 27990 WAS REPORTED LEAKING BY YARD PERSONNEL.  MGR.. RODABOUGH ARRIVED AT OGDEN A APPROXIMATELY 1000 HRS., MET WITH THE RIVERDALE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND TOOK THEM INTO THE YARD, WHERE WE ESTABLISHED A COMMAND CENTER NEAR THE UPFE OFFICES LOCATED ABOUT 300 YARDS SOUTH OF THE CAR, WHICH WAS SPOTTED FIRST OUT ON THE EAST END OF #23 TRACK.  IN COMPANY WITH TOW FIRE DEPT PERSONNEL WE ENTERED THE SIGHT WITH THE AID OF SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS AND MADE INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING CAR.  LEAKING CONDITION WAS FOUND IN THE B-END LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WHERE THE VALVE IS BOLTED ONTO THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  WE WITHDREW FROM THE SIGHT AND NOTIFIED ELF ATOCHEM THE SHIPPER, THEY IN TURN ASKED IF WE HAD A RESOURCE FOR A C-KIT.  MGR.. RODABOUGH CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE WESTERN ZIRCONIUM AND THEY ARRANGED TO SEND A FOUR MAN TEAM WITH THE KIT.  THE TEAM AND KIT ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HRS.  AFTER A BRIEF SAFETY MEETING WITH THE TEAM FROM WESTERN ZIRCONIUM AND THE FIRE DEPT., INCLUDING FRA INSPECTOR RUSSELL KELLY, A FIVE MAN TEAM INCLUDING MGR. RODABOUGH ENTERED THE SIGHT AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BOLT. THIS ATTEMPT ONLY AGGRAVATED THE LEAKING SITUATION AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE C-KIT SHOULD BE APPLIED.  THE C-KIT WAS APPLIED AND THE CAR STOPPED LEAKING.  ALL YARD PERSONNEL WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO WORK AT THE CAR SHOP AND THE UPFE OFFICES, ALL SWITCH CREWS WERE ALLOWED TO COMMENCE SWITCHING OPERATIONS AT APPROXIMATELY 1320 HRS.  THE TOTAL EVACUATION EFFORT INCLUDED APPROXIMATELY 16 PERSONNEL FROM THE  SHIP AND THE UPFE AS WELL AS TWO SWITCH CREWS, NO OTHER EVACUATION WAS NECESSARY.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC PERSONNEL.  CHEMTREC WAS INFORMED, MR. ROBERT WIBLE TOOK THE REPORT AND ISSUED CASE NUMBER 02081999020.

Mobile chemical leases storage tank (No. 677) from Lyondell/ Citgo located at 12000 Lawndale , Houston, TX. This tank is used to store Dripolene. During storage, a water layer forms in the bottom of the tank. Mobil Chemical periodically contracts Bealine Service Company to remove the water layer from Tank 677 and transports back to Mobil's Houston facility for re-processing. The water is gravity fed from tank 677 into a Bealine Vacuum Tank Trailer. It normally takes 3 to 4 hours to load a trailer. Bealine driver, Tim Watkins, arrived at the Lyondell/ Citgo facility at approximately 8:30 pm on 2/7/99. The Lyondell/ Citgo guard contacted a Lyondell/ Citgo chemical pumper by radio. Mr. Watkins was instructed to proceed to Tank 677. At approximately 9:00 pm, the chemical pumper arrived at tank 677 and gave Mr. Watkins his paperwork, a two way radio and asked Mr. Watkins to contact her when he was finished loading. At approximately 00:15 hours on 2/8/99, while loading trailer 275, material overflowed from the manway. The cause of the spill was mechanical failure of the gauging device combined with human error. During loading, Mr. Watkins stated that he periodically monitored the level in the trailer. The vacuum tanker is equipped with a float gauge. The float gauge stuck giving the driver a false reading on the amount of material in the tank. Mr. Watkins states that he saw the material begin to overflow from the manway and immediately shut off the flow to the trailer. Lyondell personnel were contacted by radio and the area was secured. Allen Timme, Senior Environmental Engineer for Lyondell/ Citgo was contacted and responded to the scene. Mr. Timme took command and took action to protect exposure in the hot zone. Mr. Timme also monitored the decontamination and remediation of the area. After taking immediate action to mitigate the situation, Mr. Watkins contacted the Bealine dispatcher. At the time of the spill, we believed the spilled material was water saturated with Benzene and therefore there was no release of a reportable quantity of a hazardous substance. However, the following morning, Mr. Timme advised Richard Cirillo at Bealine that he had assumed a worst case scenario, i.e., that the spilled material was dripolene and not saturated water. Using the worst case scenario, Mr. Timme calculated that approximately 403 lbs. of benzene had been spilled. (4 barrels x 42 gallons per barrel =168 gallons x 7.5 lbs. per gallon = 1260 total lbs. x 32% = 403 lbs of benzene). The reportable quantity for benzene is 10 lbs. Upon making this determination, Mr. Timme stated that he had notified the National Response Center (report No. 473199), Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission (report No. 990266) and further contacted or attempted to contact Harris County Pollution Control, LaPorte, Pasadena and Galena Park LAPC. At 10:05 am on 2/8/99, after learning of Mr. Timme's determination, Richard Cirillo of Bealine service Company made the following teleph

Responded to small sort. Used the decision tree and response sheets for corrosive liquids. Processed the damaged portion through the DMP program. The balance was returned to the shipper. Used sodium bicarbonate to reach PH-7. Temp ID #02-12-03N. DIR# 7652843.

Responded to bay 535. Used the decision tree and response sheets for a corrosive liquid, then processed the damaged portion through the DMP and returned the balance to the shipper. Temp ID #02-11-01N. DIR# 7652833.

HE GAVE BOUDREAUX THE AUTHORIZATION TO CONTACT A CONTRACTOR. BOUDREAUX CONTACTED CET ENVIRONMENTAL AND SPOKE TO BILL DELONG  WHO RESPONDED. DELONG FOUND THAT THE TANK WAS A PRESSURE CAR AND THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM BENNEATH THE PRESSURE PLATE DUE TO A DEFECTIVE PRESSURE PLATE GASKET. DELONG WEDGE MATERIAL BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE AND THE TANK AND APPLIED AN EPOXY, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT ABOUT 1200 HRS. ON 02/023/99 AND THE TANK CAR RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO EXXON FOR UNLOADING.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY JERRY CAIN, DIRECTOR, MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, ONE SPOT REPAIR FACILITY, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE CAR REPAIR FACILITY, LOCATED THE ABOVE TANK CAR ON THE RIP TRACK, AND NOTED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE VACUUM BREAKER. THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN SET TO RIP TRACK FOR SOME REPAIR WORK, AND WHEN INSPECTED BY MECHANICAL FORCES, A HISSING SOUNG WAS NOTED COMING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE  CAR. THERE WAS VERY LITTLE PRESURRE WITHIN THE CAR AT THE TIME OF THE INSPECTION. AFTER SERVERAL ATTEMPTS TO RESET THE THE VACUUM BREAKER, THE UNIT WAS REMOVED FROM THE CARR, AND , SINCE A  REPLACEMENT UNIT WAS NOT AVAILABLE, A PIPE PLUG WAS INSTALLED IN IT'S PLACE. INSPECTION OF THE VACUUM BREAKER NOTED THE 'O' RING WAS SEVERALLY DISTORED. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER OF THE DEFECT.  ON MONDAY, FEBRUARY 15, 1999, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, AND DEVELOPED THEY HAD RECEIVED AT VOICE MESSAGE FROM SYSTECH REPORTING THE DEFECT. AS THE CAR WAS LEASED BY CHEMICAL WASTE, THEY MADE CONTACT WITH THEIR REPRESENTATIVE FROM G.E. RAIL CAR, AND REQUESTED A REPLACEEMENT UNIT BE SENT OUT. THE CAR WAS THEN REPAIED BY CHEMICAL WASTE PERSONNEL PRIOR TO RELOADING. DUE THE TYPE OF RELEASE, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE CAR LESSEE FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. RECEIVED IN INTERCHANGE-PER 49CFR 172.205(F) - NO MANIFEST AVAILABLE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE  ICTF INTERMODAL FACILITY, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA. THE ABOVE 20 FOOT CONTAINER WAS IN THE WALL OF A DOUBLE STACK CAR ALONG WITH AN ADDITIONAL 20 FOOTER. A SMALL POOL (ROUGHLY ONE GALLON )  OF LIQUID WAS ON THE PAVEMENT UNDER THE RAILCAR  AND THE INTERIOR OF THE DOUBLE STACK CAR WAS COVERED WITH THE LIQUID. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE CONTAINER  FROM THE CAR, AND 'DIAPER' IT TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LOSS OF PRODUCT WHILE IT WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION. ONCE THE TEAM WAS ASSEMBLED, THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED. THE LADING CONSISTED OF DOUBLE STACKED 55  GALLON METAL DRUMS.  THE TOP TIER DRUMS WERE LEANING TOWARDS THE REAR DOORS, AND AS LATER DISCOVERED,WAS DUE TO THE  CARDBOARD UTILIZED AS BILEVEL SEPARATION. THE REAR BULKHEADD, WHILE IT APPEARED TO BE WELL CONSTRUCTED, WAS NOT IN CONFORMANCE  WITH THE RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL ADDRESSED  THE ARR BOE 6C FOR THE ACTUAL WEIGHT OF THE LADING.ONCE THE BULKHEAD WAS REMOVED, IT WAS EDIDENT THE CARDBOARD UTILIZED FOR THE BILEVEL SEPARATION WAS INADEQUATE. THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUMS HAD CRUCHED THE CARDBOARD, ALLOWING THEM TO CANT TO THE REAR. ANOTHER FACTOR THAT AFFECTED THIS MOVEMENT WAS THE PLACEMENT OF PALLETS IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER TO FILL A VOID FOR THE TOP TIER. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER BOE 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. REMOVAL OF THE DRUMS COMMENCED IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM. THE FIRST DRUM AGAINST THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER, BOTTOM TIER, WAS DAMAHGED AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. BOTH THE UPPER AND LOWER ROLLING HOOPS HAD BEEN ABRADED FROM THE ADJACENT DRUM. ANOTHER DRUM WAS LOCATED FUTHER IN THE LOAD AND WAS IN THE SAME CONDITION. THE ENTIRE LOAD HAD SHIFTED, AND ROTATED DURING TRANSIT. A TOTAL OF 15 DRUMS HAD LEAKED FROM ABRASIONS TO THE ROLLING HOOPS. AN ADDITIONAL 31 DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE IN SUCH POOR  CONDITION THAT THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FUTHER TRANSPORT. ALL OF THE LEAKING AND DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACEDINTO OVERPACKEDS TO SECURE THEM. AS THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, A REPLACEMENT CONTAINER, HJCU 742813, WAS BROUGHT IN TO FACILITATE THE  REROAD. ONCE THE RELOAD WAS COMPLETED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR BILLING. THE RAILCAR AND ORIGINAL CONTAINER WERE CLEANED PER THE MANUFACTURERS RECOMMENDATION. DUE TO THE AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES,AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Hose; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON FEBRUARY 16, 1999 AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 P.M., COUNTRY LINES, INC., HAD A SPILL OF GASOLINE AND DIESEL PRODUCTS AT SUPER SODA RT. 50, 28768 OCEAN HIGHWAY, SALISBURY, MARYLAND 21801.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY AN ACCIDENT IN WHICH A VEHICLE DRIVEN BY JAMES RIDDICK STRUCK A COUNTRY LINES TRANSPORT TANKER DRIVEN BY ROBERT LEE FAULCON TEARING OFF THE FIVE FILL VALVES AND THE PIPING LEADING TO THE TANKER POTS.  THE VEHICLE ALSO DAMAGED THE INTERNAL SAFETY VALVES ON 4 OUT OF 5 POTS CAUSING THE TANKER TO LOSE ITS PRODUCT IN A STORM DRAIN LEADING TO A BRANCH OF MITCHELL POND. THE STATION BEING DELIVERED TO WAS UNDER CONSTRUCTION AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. MR. FAULCON WAS ATTEMPTING TO ENTER THE STORE FROM THE WEST ENTRANCE IN ORDER TO DRIVE AROUND THE STORE AND GET TO THE TANKS WHICH HAD JUST BEEN SUNK.  AFTER ENTERING THE LOT MR. FAULCON DISCOVERED THAT HE COULD NOT GET AROUND THE STORE WITH THE TRANSPORT BECAUSE OF AN AREA THAT WAS BEING USED FOR SOIL REMEDIATION.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE MR. FAULCON WAS ATTEMPTING TO BACK OUT OF THE STATION WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF TWO EMPLOYEES OF EPS, THE COMPANY RENOVATING THE STORE.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE ON RT. 50 ATTEMPTING TO STOP TRAFFIC WHILE MR. FAULCON, BACKED OUT OF THE STORE WHEN THE TANKER WAS STRUCK BY MR. RIDDICK.  CHARGES FOR BOTH PARTIES ARE STILL PENDING. IMMEDIATELY RESPONDING ACCIDENT WERE THE SALISBURY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MARYLAND STATE POLICE.  THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT RESPONDED FROM ANNAPOLIS.  ALSO RESPONDING WERE THE U.S. COAST GUARD AND THE MARYLAND STATE HIGHWAY ADMINISTRATION. MICHAEL K. DAVIS, PRESIDENT OF COUNTRY LINES ALSO IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  SOIL FROM THE CONSTRUCTION SITE WAS USED TO ATTEMPT TO CONTAIN SOME OF THE SPILL.  THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCTS SPILLED IN A STORM DRAIN THAT DUMPED INTO A BRANCH OF MITCHELL POND.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE BRANCH BY THE NATURAL TOPOGRAPHY OF THE AREA. A&A ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS HIRED BY COUNTRY LINES, INC., AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 P.M., THE DAY OF THE ACCIDENT TO CONTAIN AND CLEANUP THE SPILL.  A MID-EASTERN OIL PUMP TRUCK AND A TAYLOR OIL TRANSPORT WERE USED TO RECOVER 3,075 GALLONS FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER: 5,426 GALLONS WERE SPILLED. SUCTION TRUCKS FROM A&A ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND CLEAN HARBORS WERE USED TO RECOVER PRODUCT FROM THE WATER SURFACE OF THE MITCHELL POND BRANCH. THE LIQUIDS WERE TANKEN TO IPC IN BALTIMORE, MD.  A&A ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WILL CONTINUE TO MONITOR THE SITE FOR ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE FROM MDE.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 16, 1999 AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 P.M., COUNTRY LINES, INC., HAD A SPILL OF GASOLINE AND DIESEL PRODUCTS AT SUPER SODA RT. 50, 28768 OCEAN HIGHWAY, SALISBURY, MARYLAND 21801.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY AN ACCIDENT IN WHICH A VEHICLE DRIVEN BY JAMES RIDDICK STRUCK A COUNTRY LINES TRANSPORT TANKER DRIVEN BY ROBERT LEE FAULCON TEARING OFF THE FIVE FILL VALVES AND THE PIPING LEADING TO THE TANKER POTS.  THE VEHICLE ALSO DAMAGED THE INTERNAL SAFETY VALVES ON 4 OUT OF 5 POTS CAUSING THE TANKER TO LOSE ITS PRODUCT IN A STORM DRAIN LEADING TO A BRANCH OF MITCHELL POND. THE STATION BEING DELIVERED TO WAS UNDER CONSTRUCTION AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. MR. FAULCON WAS ATTEMPTING TO ENTER THE STORE FROM THE WEST ENTRANCE IN ORDER TO DRIVE AROUND THE STORE AND GET TO THE TANKS WHICH HAD JUST BEEN SUNK.  AFTER ENTERING THE LOT MR. FAULCON DISCOVERED THAT HE COULD NOT GET AROUND THE STORE WITH THE TRANSPORT BECAUSE OF AN AREA THAT WAS BEING USED FOR SOIL REMEDIATION.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE MR. FAULCON WAS ATTEMPTING TO BACK OUT OF THE STATION WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF TWO EMPLOYEES OF EPS, THE COMPANY RENOVATING THE STORE.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE ON RT. 50 ATTEMPTING TO STOP TRAFFIC WHILE MR. FAULCON, BACKED OUT OF THE STORE WHEN THE TANKER WAS STRUCK BY MR. RIDDICK.  CHARGES FOR BOTH PARTIES ARE STILL PENDING. IMMEDIATELY RESPONDING ACCIDENT WERE THE SALISBURY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MARYLAND STATE POLICE.  THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT RESPONDED FROM ANNAPOLIS. column168: PACKAGE UNLOADED OFF TRAILER, SENT DOWN BELT.  MARK ORBITZ PICKED UP BOX TO GIVE TO CLERK FOR NEW 5 PART FORM LABEL.  CLERK DISCOVERED LEAK, NOTIFIED SUP.  HE CALLED RESPONDER WHO PUT ON APRON BOOTS AND GOGGLES, GLOVES.  PUT PACKAGE IN LINED BUCKET FOLLOWED DECISION TREE RAN THRU DMP HAD PEOPLE INVOLVED WASH HANDS.

I RESPONDED TO SPILL ON HUDSON BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. PACKAGE WAS LABELED WITH THE PROPER IDENTIFICATION MARKINGS FOR THIS TYPE OF RESPONSE. I PERFORMED A PH TO CONFIRM THIS AND PH READ BETWEEN-9. RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAD ME ABSORB SPILLAGE WITH SPEEDY DRY AND I ALSO USED ACTIVATED CARBON TO CONTROL THE ODOR. SCBA GEAR WAS WORN AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE TO ENABLE THE REMAINDER OF SPILL TO BE PROPERLY HANDLED. THIS WAS PERFORMED IN THE DMP AREA. ALL REMAINING CONTAINERS  IN CARTON WERE RETURNED TO SHIPPER IN A HAZARDOUS SALVAGE DRUM. BETTER PACKAGING AND HANDLING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS SPILL.

I RESPONDED TO SPILL ON PUTNAM BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. LITMUS TEST READ BETWEEN 6-9.LITMUS RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. I ABSORBED LIQUID WITH SPEEDY DRY AND ACTIVATED CARBON FOR STRONG ODORS. PACKAGE WAS THEN PROCESSED IN THE DMP AREA. I RETURNED HAZARDOUS PORTION IN  A THE DMP AREA. I RETURNED HAZARDOUS PORTION IN A HAZARDOUS SALVAGE DRUM TO SHIPPER. OTHER ITEMS WERE ALSO RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER THAT WERE NON-HAZARDOUS IN A CARDBOARD BOX. BETTER PACKAGING AND HANDLING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS SPILL.

RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN AND RESULTS OF TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. I USED SPEEDY DRY TO ABSORB REMAINDER OF LIQUID THAT WAS NOT ABSORBED BY THE CARDBOARD. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PROCESSED IN THE DMP AREA. BETTER PACKAGEING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS SPILL. (B) I RESPONDED TO SPILL ON PRIMARY BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. CUSTOMER'S FILL WAS OLDER TYPE REQUIRING USE OF A "CONE NOZZLE".  NOZZLE CAME OUT OF FILL PIPE AND APPROX. 3 GALLONS SPILLED INTO YARD & BUSHES. DRIVER & TWO SERVICE TECHS CLEANED YARD AND WE LATER REMEDIATED DAMAGE TO BUSHES BY REPLACING THEM.  FILL WAS REPLACED WITH NEWER TYPE TO PREVENT RECURRANCE. column168: THESE REINFORCED PLASTIC CONTAINERS NO LONGER EXIST.  AFTER THIS INCIDENT OUR FORMER ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, BURT MCKEE HAD ALL THE CONTAINERS INSPECTED FOR POSSIBLE SUN DAMAGE.  AFTER DETERMINING THAT THE CONTAINERS WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO PROVIDE SUFFICIENT INTEGRITY WHEN EXPOSED TO FLORIDA WEATHER CONDITIONS,  MR. MCKEE INSTRUCTED THAT THEY BE DESTROYED. THE METAL REINFORCEMENT MATERIAL WAS OFFERED LOCALLY FOR RECYCLING.  SINCE UNITED AGRI PRODUCTS WAS THE CONTRACTOR FOR PESTICIDE CONTAINER RECYCLING IN FLORIDA, MR. MCKEE INSTRUCTED THAT THE PLASTIC COMPONENTS BE SHREDDED AND INCORPORATED INTO THAT PROGRAM. PLASTIC FROM THAT PROGRAM IS EITHER RECYCLED INTO A NEW CONTAINER, OR IS BURNED FOR ENERGY.

ON FEBRUARY 3, 1999 AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 AM, A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF NO. 6 FUEL OIL OCCURRED AT THE SITE.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN TRUCK SERVICES, INC.  OF SHREWSBURY, MASSACHUSETTS DELIVERED OIL TO A TEMPORARY ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK (FRAC TANK) LOCATED AT THE SITE.  A TANK OVERFILL OCCURRED WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF NO. 6 FUEL OIL TO THE SIDES OF THE 22,500-GALLON CAPACITY FRAC TANK THE TEMPORARY BERM BENEATH THE TANK, THE ADJACENT PAVEMENT SURFACE, AND SUBSEQUENTLY ENTERED A STORM DRAIN SYSTEM WHICH DISCHARGES TO THE ADJACENT NASHUA RIVER.  THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION (DEP) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM ON FEBRUARY 3, 1999 BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC.  (CHES) ON BEHALF OF FITCHBURG OPERATING. CHES SPOKE WITH MR. KEVIN DAOUST OF THE BUREAU OF WASTE SITE CLEANUP, WHO VERBALLY APPROVED PLANS TO CONDUCT AN IRA.  APPROVED IRA ACTIVITIES INCLUDED APPLYING ABSORBANTS TO THE RELEASE AREA, PUMPING LIQUID FROM THE IMPACTED CATCH BASIN, REMOVAL OF UP TO 10 CUBIC YARDS OF IMPACTED SOIL ALONG THE BANK OF THE NASHUA RIVER, AND CLEANING OF THE IMPACTED DRAINAGE SYSTEM.

column168: ON FEB 9, 1999 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM, A GASOLINE SPILL OCCURRED WHILE DRIVER DANNY PHELPS WAS FILLING UNDER-GROUND TANKS AT SUMMER SHADE SERVICE AT 2340 SUMMER SHADE RD., SUMMER SHADE, KY.  APPROXIMATELY 30-40 GALLONS WERE ALLOWED TO BE SPILLED ONTO THE PAVED PARKING LOT AND ONTO HWY 90. FUEL SPILL HEADED AND CONTAINED USING OIL DRY PRODUCT, PREVENTING ANY FROM ENTERING ANY WATER-WAY.  SPILL LIMITED TO APPROX. AREA OF 6' X 25' OF PARKING LOT AND APPROXIMATELY 15' X 15' ON HWY 90.  GASOLINE CONTAINED AND ABSORBED BY THE OIL DRY.  CONTAINMINATED OIL DRY SWEPT UP, BAGGED AND CURRENTLY STORED AT SUMMER SHADE SERVICE AWAITING DISPOSAL INSTRUCTIONS. DAVID COOMER OF THE DEPT. FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION OF COLUMBIA KY, INFORMED FIRE CHIEF AND BUSINESS OWNER, DALE ROWLETT THAT MATERIAL COULD NOT BE BURNED BUT MUST BE DISPOSED OF IN ANOTHER MANNER.  REPORT OF THE SPILL MADE TO CHEMTREC, IN ACCORDANCE WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND DES, PROTOCOL.  REPORT MADE BY DAVID WHITE, ON INSTRUCTIONS BY CHIEF DALE ROWLETT, AT APPROXIMATELY 3:45 PM ON 2-9-99.  REPORTED SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 45 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND NONE HAD ENTGERED ANY WATERWAYS. SPILL OCCURRED BY DRIVER, CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY FIRE DEPT. AND RESCUE DEPT. PEROSNNEL, AND MATERIALS ARE CURRENTLY STORED ON PREMISES AWAITING DISPOSAL INSTRUCTIONS.  ANY FURTHER QUESTIONS MAY BE DIRECTED TO DALE ROWLETT, OR DAVID COOMER OF THE DEPT. FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AT 502-384-4735
